<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Brassica tournefortii, </i>Asian mustard, has a Cal-IPC rank of High. This mustard is a winter annual with small, yellow flowers with plants to 1 m in height. It is a relatively recent introduction, becoming a major weed in the hot deserts and in southeastern California in the last few decades. Dense stands suppress native wildflowers, especially in sandy settings. The effect is most notable in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park and certain parts of the eastern Colorado Desert between Blythe and Palm Springs. Because of its early germination and rapid development, it uses early soil moisture and sets seed before many natives develop. It also has faster development than <i>B. rapa </i>and <i>Hirschfeldia incana, </i>which are not invasive in the Mojave Desert (Marushia and Holt 2005).<br/>
<br/>
Stands with <i>Brassica tournefortii, Malcolmia africana </i>and <i>Sisymbrium irio</i>are beginning to expand in desert areas of the southwest United States, including at Mojave National Preserve and Joshua Tree National Park (Evens et al. 2014, Abella et al. 2015), especially on sandier soils. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Brassica tournefortii </i>stands were previously treated under the <i>Brassica nigra</i> and other mustards Semi-Natural Alliance in the 2009 edition of <i>A Manual of California Vegetation</i>. </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands of <i>B. tournefortii </i>in Joshua Tree National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2005), in the Granite Mountains of the Mojave National Preserve and throughout the Mojave Desert (322A; Thomas et al. 2004) are on sandy soils.  Stands were mapped in the western Mojave and Chuckwalla Valley subsection of the Sonoran Desert (322B; Menke et al. 2016). Evens and Hartman (2007) recognized stands of <i>B. tournefortii </i>on sandy soils. </div>
</div>

	

    
